A @{ } hole in a JS binding/lvalue position (here a declaration name) is
rejected unless its Go type is gsx.RawJS. The classifier defers the position to
JSCtxBinding; the rejection is now an emit-time diagnostic (jsx-binding-position)
gated on the type. `name` is a plain string, not gsx.RawJS, so it is rejected.

-- input.gsx --
package views

component Page(name string) {
	<script>
		let @{ name } = 1;
	</script>
}
-- diagnostics.golden --
5:8: @{ } here is a JavaScript binding/lvalue position (assignment target, declaration or member name); only a gsx.RawJS value may be spliced here — wrap it as gsx.RawJS(...) if the bytes are trusted, or use it where a value is expected
